ce:section.ce:para:
In this work, a highly efficient laminated LSC with multi-emission is prepared by using blue-white light emitting carbon dots (BWCDs) and green/red emitting CsPbBr3/CsPbI3 quantum dots (G/RQDs) as fluorophores (Fig. 1
                     ). First, BWCDs with high PLQY of 13.82 % and G/RQDs (PLQYs of 68.29 % and 71.05 %, respectively) are synthesized. Then, the BWCDs based laminated LSCs are prepared by one-step photopolymerization method, followed by coating G and RQDs on bottom and top glass surfaces of laminated BWCDs LSCs, respectively, finally forming multi-emission laminated LSCs. More importantly, the multi-emission LSCs show multi-PL emission peaks (450, 515 and 670 nm), covering the entire visible ranges. Moreover, the multi-emission LSCs exhibit high performances: an η
                     opt of ∼ 3.76 % is obtained, representing a 176 % enhancement in efficiency over BWCDs based single-emission LSCs. The multi-emission strategy can effectively simulate the sunlight spectrum, enabling the multi-emission LSCs with high performances and posing great potential for practical applications in the future BIPVs.

Relying on the large Stokes shift and high PLQYs, the BWCDs, G/RQDs have been applied for fabrication of single emission LSCs. First, all the single emission LSCs have good transparency, the “letters” under the LSCs are clearly seen (Fig. 4
                        a, c, e). On the other hand, the PL emission of white, green, and red colors are clearly seen, as shown in Fig. 4b, d, f. Their edges of all LSCs show intense PL emission owing to the waveguide effect. To further demonstrate the optical properties, the absorption, transparence, and PL emission of LSCs at various concentrations of BWCDs and G/RQDs, have been conducted (Fig. 5
                        ). As shown in Fig. 5a, d, g, all the single emission LSCs show similar absorption behavior with different concentrations of BWCDs and G/RQDs. Their absorption increase with the increased concentrations of fluorescent materials. Correspondingly, the transmittance of all the single emission LSCs decrease gradually with the increased concentrations of fluorescent materials, as shown in Fig. 5b, e, h. At least 40 % transmittance at visible range is obtained even at 13.9 wt% of BWCDs concentration, 13.1 wt% GQDs concentration, and 10.7 wt% RQDs concentration. However, the PL emission shows different trend: the PL emission intensities of BWCDs based LSCs appear to first increase and then decrease once increasing the CDs concentrations from 0.4 to 13.9 wt% and the maximum PL emission is at 4.4 wt% of CDs concentration, probably resulted from the aggregation-caused quenching (ACQ) effect in CDs-based system [33,34]. Thus, the BWCDs based LSCs with 4.4 wt% of CDs concentration will be an optimal condition for achieving LSCs with high performances. Otherwise, with the increased G/RQDs concentrations, the PL emission intensities of G/RQDs enhance gradually, as shown in Fig. 5f, i. It is noted that all the single emission LSCs show similar PL emission peaks with that of fluorescent materials in solution state (Fig. 3a-c).
